 (55,'Mahabharata - Retold by Krishna Dharma',36,'MAHABHARATA, TORCHLIGHT,','The Greatest Spiritual Epic of All Time by Krishna Dharma â€” World\'s Best-selling Edition\r\n\r\nAn exciting and profound story of life in ancient times, Mahabharata is at once a fascinating epic and a compendium of ethical and spiritual teachings. Krishna Dharma presents a compelling version of this most cherished of all Indian classics, in the highly readable style of a contemporary novel.\r\n\r\nIlluminating and deeply moving, it is the story of five heroic warriors, the Pandavas, who are robbed of their kingdom and exiled. We are taken with them on an extraordinary journey, meeting sages, kings, demons, heroines, and celestial beings. Culminating in the greatest war of all time, Mahabharata is a masterpiece of adventure, intrigue, romance, and spiritual wisdom.\r\n\r\n2000 Benjamin Franklin Award Finalist to Mahabharata:\r\nISBN: 978-1-887089-17-3\r\nIllustration: 16 color plates, 20 illustrations\r\nPages: 960',750,1,'uploads/items/55XX1406215969.jpg',1406215969,'1',1406216508,'800',120),
 (56,'Ramayana - Retold by Krishna Dharma',36,'ramayana, ISKCON, valmiki, krishna, dharma, torchlight','India\'s Immortal Tale of Adventure, Love and Wisdom â€” World\'s Best-selling Edition\r\n\r\nRevered throughout the ages for its moral and spiritual wisdom, it is a beautiful and uplifting tale of romance and high adventure, recounting the odyssey of Rama, a great king of ancient India.\r\n\r\nThrough some political trickery, Rama is exiled to the forest for fourteen years, where his brother Lakshmana and beautiful wife Sita, faithfully accompany him. There, Sita is kidnapped by the powerful demon Ravana. Along with Lakshmana and a fantastic army of supernatural creatures, Rama starts on a perilous quest to find his beloved Sita.\r\n\r\nISBN: 978-1-887089-22-7\r\nIllustration: 8 color plates, 10 illustrations\r\nPages: 488',515,5,'uploads/items/56XX1406216135.jpg',1406216135,'1',NULL,'550',100),
 (57,'Art Treasures of the Mahabharata',36,'Mahabharata, ISKCON, delhi, Vedic, Expo, Museum,','Dive into the magnificient treasury of India\'s glorious past! Exquisitely crafted high-reliek sculpture brings to life the essential beauty, splendor, and nobility of the Mahabharata, India\'s greatest spiritual epic.\r\n\r\nArt Treasures of the Mahabharata is a collection of captivating photographs and illustrations for a monumental work called the Glory of India, now on view in New Delhi.',460,2,'uploads/items/57XX1406216411.jpg',1406216411,'1',NULL,'500',65),
 (58,'Mahabharata Retold',36,'Mahabharata','Retold by Purnaprajna Dasa. The main story of the MahabhÃ¤rata is the history of the Kuru dynasty, and the events that led to the great battle at Kuruksetra. It begins with the lives of those from whom the Pandavas and Kauravas, the central characters of the Mahabharat, descended. The story really takes hold when Pandu dies and his wife and five sons arrive at Hastinapura, the ancient city in India, to live under the care of their blind uncle, Dhritharasthra. Besides this main story, however, there are countless other stories told when the Pandavas meet great sages while in exile, or while sitting before Grandfather Bhishma on his deathbed of arrows. This is the way that life was in former times. The arrival of a great sage would be an event to celebrate for everyone in these ancient times. They didnâ€™t have movies, computers, or television and so the great sage, who was a reservoir of histories and deep knowledge, would entertain and enlighten people with stories and the lessons to be learned from them. People would be happy to sit for hours, or even days, and listen to the stories told by the visiting sage, and they considered the lessons learned from such stories to be the essence of education.',700,2,'uploads/items/58XX1406217238.png',1406217238,'1',NULL,'800',100),
 (59,'Uddhava Gita and Mahabharat - Special Combo',36,'uddhhava, gita, mahabharata, ramayana, combo, special, offer','UDDHAVA GITA AND MAHABHARAT ARE THE RAREST OF GEMS AMONG THE TRANSCENDENTAL LITERATURE\r\n\r\nUDDHAVA GITA\r\n\r\nBhagavad-gita was spoken by Lord Krishna to His friend Arjuna, on the battlefield of Kuruksetra, when the later refused to execute his duty fearing the death of many family members; in order to induce Arjuna to fight as a matter of duty, Bhagavad-gita was spoken. Uddhava gita was also spoken by the same Lord Krishna, to another dear and intimate devotee, Sri Uddhava. Uddhava-gita was spoken by Lord Krishna to Uddhava to exceute the final duty of this world â€“ which is renunciation of all worldly attachments and take to the path of complete dedication to God. In essence, messages of Bhagavad-gita and Uddhava-gita are similar, but Uddhava-gita goes little bit further in the science of God. Lord Krishna instructed Arjuna at the end of Bhagavad-gita to abandone all varieties of religions and simply surrender to Him, and to execute His will only. So Arjuna did just that, as the Lord had instructed.\r\n\r\nThis book, Uddhava Gita, with commentaries of Srila Visvanatha Cakravarti Thakura and Srila Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati Thakura, is complete with the original sanskrit verses, roman transliterations, english translations, and full commentaries. At the end of the book are glossaries of the terms used, and full index. The book is 820 pages, 9\"x7\", hardback.\r\n\r\nMAHABHARAT\r\n\r\nRetold by Purnaprajna Dasa The main story of the MahabhÃ¤rata is the history of the Kuru dynasty, and the events that led to the great battle at Kuruksetra. It begins with the lives of those from whom the Pandavas and Kauravas, the central characters of the Mahabharat, descended. The story really takes hold when Pandu dies and his wife and five sons arrive at Hastinapura, the ancient city in India, to live under the care of their blind uncle, Dhritharasthra. Besides this main story, however, there are countless other stories told when the Pandavas meet great sages while in exile, or while sitting before Grandfather Bhishma on his deathbed of arrows. This is the way that life was in former times. The arrival of a great sage would be an event to celebrate for everyone in these ancient times. They didnâ€™t have movies, computers, or television and so the great sage, who was a reservoir of histories and deep knowledge, would entertain and enlighten people with stories and the lessons to be learned from them. People would be happy to sit for hours, or even days, and listen to the stories told by the visiting sage, and they considered the lessons learned from such stories to be the essence of education.',1175,2,'uploads/items/59XX1406217453.jpg',1406217453,'1',NULL,'1400',200),
 (60,'Uddhava Gita',36,'Gita, Krishna, uddhava','UDDHAVA GITA\r\n\r\nBhagavad-gita was spoken by Lord Krishna to His friend Arjuna, on the battlefield of Kuruksetra, when the later refused to execute his duty fearing the death of many family members; in order to induce Arjuna to fight as a matter of duty, Bhagavad-gita was spoken. Uddhava gita was also spoken by the same Lord Krishna, to another dear and intimate devotee, Sri Uddhava. Uddhava-gita was spoken by Lord Krishna to Uddhava to exceute the final duty of this world â€“ which is renunciation of all worldly attachments and take to the path of complete dedication to God. In essence, messages of Bhagavad-gita and Uddhava-gita are similar, but Uddhava-gita goes little bit further in the science of God. Lord Krishna instructed Arjuna at the end of Bhagavad-gita to abandone all varieties of religions and simply surrender to Him, and to execute His will only. So Arjuna did just that, as the Lord had instructed.\r\n\r\nThis book, Uddhava Gita, with commentaries of Srila Visvanatha Cakravarti Thakura and Srila Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati Thakura, is complete with the original sanskrit verses, roman transliterations, english translations, and full commentaries. At the end of the book are glossaries of the terms used, and full index. The book is 820 pages, 9\"x7\", hardback.',650,2,'uploads/items/60XX1406218086.png',1406218086,'1',NULL,'750',120),
 (61,'Prince Rama - The Son of Solar Dynasty',11,'Ramayana, Children','Prince in Exile is the first in a three volume translation of Indiaâ€™s literary masterpiece â€“ Ramayana. There are many versions of this classic written for adults, but very few exist that have so carefully retold the spellbinding epic of Lord Rama along with its universal moral and spiritual lessons in such an attractive manner for children.\r\n\r\nThis set, Prince Rama, Son of the Solar Dynasty, is not only a feast for the eyes, but also for the ears and heart. An exceptionally talented mother and daughter team have created one of the most beautiful childrenâ€™s Ramayana ever published. Children of all ages will be fascinated by Annapurnaâ€™s delightful illustrations and Vrindaâ€™s mesmerizing narration.\r\n\r\nISBN: 978-0-981727-31-8\r\nIllustration:16 color plates\r\nPages: 212',675,1,'uploads/items/61XX1406220957.jpg',1406220896,'1',1406220957,'750',75),
